          <physDesc>
            <objectDesc form="codex">
              <supportDesc material="chart">
                <foliation/>
                <collation/>
                <condition>
                  <list>
                    <item>
                      <p>Paper, about 9 7/8 in. by 6 5/8, consisting of 268 leaves, some of which
                        are much stained and torn, especially foll. 1, 2, 42,43, and 257—268. The
                        quires, signed with letters, are 35 in number. Leaves are wanting after
                        foll. 106, 120, 247 and 267. There are from 22 to 34 lines in each page.</p>
                      <p>Fol. 1 is so much torn, that the notes written upon it are no longer intelligible.</p>
                    </item>
                  </list>
                </condition>
              </supportDesc>
            </objectDesc>
            <handDesc hands="6">
              <handNote medium="unknown" xml:id="handNote1" scope="major" script="syr">
                <desc>This volume is written in a rather peculiar hand of the <date calendar="Gregorian" notBefore="0600" notAfter="0800">xiith or xiiith
                    cent.</date></desc>
              </handNote>
              <handNote medium="unknown" xml:id="handNote2" scope="minor" script="syr">
                <desc>Foll. 44 and 268 are somewhat more modern.</desc>
              </handNote>
              <handNote medium="unknown" xml:id="handNote3" scope="minor" script="syr">
                <desc>A later hand has inserted two lessons from the Pauline Epistles.</desc>
              </handNote>
              <handNote medium="unknown" xml:id="handNote4" scope="minor" script="syr">
                <desc>Fol. 268 contains a <foreign xml:lang="syr">ܣܘܓܝܬܐ</foreign> for the
                  Resurrection, written by a different hand.</desc>
              </handNote>
              <handNote medium="unknown" xml:id="handNote5" scope="minor" script="syr">
                <desc>The prayer on fol. 2 a is apparently in the same handwriting as the note by
                  the <persName>priest Ibrahim or Abraham</persName>, see additions.</desc>
              </handNote>
              <handNote medium="unknown" xml:id="handNote6" scope="minor" script="mixed">
                <desc>See additions.</desc>
              </handNote>
            </handDesc>
            <additions>
              <p/>
              <list>
                <item xml:id="addition1" n="1">
                  <locus from="1"/>
                  <p>The notes written upon fol. 1 are no longer intelligible.</p>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="addition2" n="2">
                  <locus from="268b"/>
                  <p>On fol. 268 b there is a note in Syriac and Arabic, by a priest named <persName>Ibrāhīm or Abraham</persName>, dated <origDate datingMethod="Seleucid" when-custom="1558">A. Gr. 1558</origDate>, <origDate calendar="Gregorian" when="1247">A.D. 1247.</origDate> The Arabic text is the better preserved.</p>
                  <p>
                    <quote xml:lang="ar">القس ابرهيم من ال .... سنه الف وخمسمايه وثمنيه وخمسين من سنين لاسكندر ابن
                      اليوناني في عشين يوم من حٍٍ[زيران] يوم الثلثه ء....</quote>
                  </p>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="addition3" n="3">
                  <locus from="268b"/>
                  <p>There is another note on fol. 268 b, in which the priest <persName>Daniel</persName>, from the village of <placeName>Hagūlī</placeName> mentions that he read this volume twice, once at <placeName> Haguli</placeName>, and again at the village of <placeName>Benīsa</placeName>.</p>
                  <p>
                    <quote xml:lang="syr">ܦܓ̣ܥ ܒܟܬܒܐ ܗܢܐ ܘܩܪܝ ܒܗ ܒܩܪܝܬܐ ܚܓܘܠܝ. ܘܬܘܒ ܙܒܢ̣ܬܐ ܐܚܪܝܬܐ
                      ܒܩܪܝܬܐ ܒܢܝܣܗ ܩܫܝܫܐ ܕܢܝܐܝܠ ܕܡܢ ܚܓܘܠܝ. ܨ̈ܠܘ ܥܠܝ ܒܒܥܘ ܡܛܠ ܡܫܝܚܐ.</quote>
                  </p>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="addition4" n="4">
                  <locus from="268b"/>
                  <p><persName>The priest Daniel</persName>, the author of the above note, has add in Arabic and Latin:</p>
                  <p>
                    <quote xml:lang="ar">الاهم اغفر لعبدك المدعيا القس دنيال</quote>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <quote xml:lang="la">amen micerere mei deus</quote>
                  </p>
                </item>
              </list>
            </additions>
